# Rule 6: Typed Boundaries (Infrastructure)

## Context

Untrusted data enters through HTTP controllers and leaves through databases and gateways. Validation errors must be **localized** at these boundaries so `/domain` never sees raw strings without structure.

## Directive

- Controllers MUST parse request bodies/params with **Zod** (or `@effect/schema` / `Schema` when using Effect end-to-end).
- Repositories that talk to SQL MUST live in files named `sql_<aggregate>.repository.ts` (or similar `sql_*.ts`).
- External HTTP clients MUST live in `http_<system>.gateway.ts` files.
- Map validation failures to HTTP or application errors **before** calling domain logic.

## Examples

### Compliant (DO)

```typescript
import { z } from 'zod';

export const CreateUserBody = z.object({
  email: z.string().email(),
  name: z.string().min(1),
});

export type CreateUserBody = z.infer<typeof CreateUserBody>;
```

```typescript
// File: sql_user.repository.ts
export class SqlUserRepository implements UserRepositoryPort {
  // ...
}
```

### Non-Compliant (DON'T)

```typescript
// Controller accepts any shape; domain receives unvalidated input.
@Post()
create(@Body() body: any) {
  return this.service.create(body);
}
```

